  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>One of the most frequently misapplied rules in investment property tax returns involves the distinction between repairs and capital improvements. The error is easy to make because the physical work can look identical. A tradesperson installs a new roof: is that a deductible repair or a non-deductible capital expense? The answer depends on specifics, and getting it wrong has consequences both in the year of the work and at the eventual sale. For Brisbane investors who are preparing to sell, the distinction also affects how your cost base is calculated.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the ATO means by a repair</h2>
      <p>A repair, in the ATO's treatment of rental properties, is work that restores something to its original working condition without making it substantially different or better than it was. The key test is whether the character of the item has changed. Common examples that typically qualify as repairs include fixing a broken fence section (not replacing the entire fence), replacing a small number of damaged roof tiles after a storm, repainting weathered exterior timber to restore protection, fixing a leaking tap or replacing a single section of plumbing that has failed, and patching damaged plaster in a specific area.</p>

      <p>Repairs of this kind are fully deductible as rental expenses in the financial year they are incurred. They reduce your taxable rental income dollar for dollar, and they do not affect your cost base. A repair does not add value to the property in the ATO's view; it simply maintains the value that was already there.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What counts as a capital improvement</h2>
      <p>A capital improvement is work that makes the property better than it was, extends its useful life, or replaces an entire asset rather than a component. Examples include replacing the entire roof (as opposed to repairing damaged sections), installing a new kitchen where there was an old functional one, adding a bathroom to the property, building a deck, pergola, or carport that did not previously exist, installing ducted air conditioning in a property that previously had none, and replacing all the windows in the property with double glazing.</p>

      <p>Capital improvements are not immediately deductible against rental income. Instead, they are either depreciated under Division 43 (the building allowance, at 2.5% per year for eligible construction) or classified as plant and equipment under Division 40 and depreciated over the effective life of each item. This means the tax benefit is spread over many years, not taken in the year of the expenditure.</p>

      <p>The other critical consequence is that capital improvements increase your cost base, which reduces the capital gain at sale. This is actually a tax advantage at the point of sale, not a disadvantage. The problem arises when investors have not kept adequate records of the capital works they have done, and those improvements cannot be added to the cost base because there is no documentation. That leads to a higher CGT liability than is legally necessary.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The initial repairs trap</h2>
      <p>There is a specific rule that catches many investors who acquire a property that needs work. If you buy a property that is in poor condition and carries out repairs shortly after purchase, the ATO treats those repairs as capital expenditure, not as deductible repairs, even if the work is technically restoring something to its original condition. The reasoning is that the poor condition of the property was known at the time of purchase and was reflected in the price paid. The repairs are therefore part of the cost of acquiring the property in a usable state, not a maintenance cost during ownership.</p>

      <p>The practical implication: if you buy a rental property, carry out significant work in the first twelve months, and your accountant claims those costs as immediate repairs deductions, there is a meaningful risk that the ATO would disallow them on audit. The safer treatment is to capitalise initial repairs and include them in the cost base. This does not mean you lose the tax benefit; it means the benefit is realised differently, either as depreciation over time or as a cost base addition at sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The grey zone: partial replacements</h2>
      <p>Many real-world scenarios fall between a clear repair and a clear capital improvement. Replacing several sections of timber decking that have rotted while retaining the remainder of the deck structure is probably a repair. Replacing the entire deck surface because the timber is at the end of its life is probably a capital improvement. Replacing a few gutters after storm damage is a repair. Replacing the entire guttering system across the property is more likely capital.</p>

      <p>The ATO does not draw these lines with mathematical precision. The character of the work matters, and the extent of the replacement relative to the whole asset matters. When the work is genuinely ambiguous, a conservative treatment is to capitalise it, document your reasoning, and discuss it with your accountant. An aggressive repair claim that is later disallowed creates a tax shortfall with interest and potentially penalties. Capitalising conservatively costs you the immediate deduction but does not create retrospective liability.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What this means for Brisbane sellers</h2>
      <p>If you are preparing to sell an investment property in Brisbane, the practical thing to do before you list is to review what capital expenditure you have made during ownership and confirm with your accountant how each item has been treated in your tax returns. This matters for two reasons. First, to confirm that your returns are accurate and that any audit risk is understood. Second, to ensure that all eligible capital works are included in your cost base calculation, so that your CGT liability at sale is not higher than it needs to be.</p>

      <p>Investors who have owned a property for ten or more years and carried out significant work, a kitchen renovation, new flooring throughout, air conditioning installation, bathroom upgrades, often underestimate the cumulative amount of capital expenditure they have made. If that expenditure has been properly capitalised and documented, it can meaningfully reduce the capital gain. If records were not kept, reconstructing the costs from invoices and bank records before the sale closes is well worth the time it takes.</p>

      <p>The other timing consideration is pre-sale work carried out to prepare the property for the market. Freshening up paintwork, repairing obvious maintenance items, and cleaning are generally deductible if the property is still available for rent during preparation (check this with your accountant depending on timing). Significant renovation work to increase sale appeal is more likely to be capital. Getting clarity on this before you start the work, rather than after, avoids a mismatch between your expectations and your actual tax position.</p>

